1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,923
You're listening to: ML-KEM vs ML-DSA: NIST's Post-Quantum Standards Explained.

2
00:00:06,923 --> 00:00:17,932
ML-KEM (FIPS 203) and ML-DSA (FIPS 204) solve two different problems — key exchange vs digital signatures.

3
00:00:17,932 --> 00:00:26,274
A clear, developer-focused explainer on what each does, their security levels, key and signature sizes, and when to use which.

4
00:00:26,274 --> 00:00:27,319
Let's get started.

5
00:00:27,319 --> 00:00:36,057
When teams start their post-quantum journey, the first confusion is almost always the same: "Do I need ML-KEM or ML-DSA?"

6
00:00:36,057 --> 00:00:41,045
The short answer is usually both — because they solve two completely different problems.

7
00:00:41,045 --> 00:00:44,411
ML-KEM gets two parties a shared secret.

8
00:00:44,411 --> 00:00:46,887
ML-DSA proves who signed something.

9
00:00:46,887 --> 00:00:53,641
Confusing them is like confusing Diffie-Hellman with RSA signatures: related field, different jobs.

10
00:00:53,641 --> 00:00:56,093
This is the developer-focused explainer.

11
00:00:56,093 --> 00:01:01,610
For the bigger picture of how to migrate, read the practical PQC migration guide first.

12
00:01:01,610 --> 00:01:05,048
Now, let's talk about The two problems cryptography has to solve.

13
00:01:05,048 --> 00:01:09,783
Almost all public-key cryptography exists to do one of two things:

14
00:01:09,783 --> 00:01:17,187
Agree on a shared secret over an insecure channel — so two parties can then use fast symmetric encryption (AES).

15
00:01:17,187 --> 00:01:22,812
Classically: Diffie-Hellman / ECDH, or RSA key transport..

16
00:01:22,812 --> 00:01:29,375
Prove authenticity and integrity — that a message came from a specific party and wasn't tampered with.

17
00:01:29,375 --> 00:01:36,658
Classically: RSA or ECDSA/Ed25519 signatures..

18
00:01:36,658 --> 00:01:41,730
Quantum computers (via Shor's algorithm) break the classical answer to both.

19
00:01:41,730 --> 00:01:44,507
NIST standardized a replacement for each:

20
00:01:44,507 --> 00:01:49,591
ML-KEM (FIPS 203) → problem 1, key exchange..

21
00:01:49,591 --> 00:01:54,879
ML-DSA (FIPS 204) → problem 2, signatures..

22
00:01:54,879 --> 00:02:08,329
Both are built on module lattices — the "ML" prefix — whose security rests on the hardness of lattice problems (Module-LWE / Module-SIS) believed to resist both classical and quantum attack.

23
00:02:08,329 --> 00:02:15,012
Moving on to ML-KEM: the key exchange (FIPS 203, formerly Kyber).

24
00:02:15,012 --> 00:02:18,329
ML-KEM is a Key Encapsulation Mechanism.

25
00:02:18,329 --> 00:02:22,067
The flow is slightly different from Diffie-Hellman, so it's worth seeing:

26
00:02:22,067 --> 00:02:25,396
Alice generates a keypair and sends Bob her public key..

27
00:02:25,396 --> 00:02:32,788
Bob runs encapsulate(public_key), which produces two things: a shared secret and a ciphertext.

28
00:02:32,788 --> 00:02:36,670
Bob keeps the secret, sends Alice the ciphertext..

29
00:02:36,670 --> 00:02:43,245
Alice runs decapsulate(ciphertext, private_key) and recovers the same shared secret..

30
00:02:43,245 --> 00:02:51,646
Now both sides hold an identical secret that never crossed the wire, and they switch to AES-256 for bulk encryption.

31
00:02:51,646 --> 00:02:56,742
ML-KEM comes in three parameter sets keyed to NIST security categories:

32
00:02:56,742 --> 00:03:00,588
Parameter set, NIST level, Roughly comparable to.

33
00:03:00,588 --> 00:03:06,141
ML-KEM-512, Category 1, AES-128.

34
00:03:06,141 --> 00:03:12,463
ML-KEM-768, Category 3, AES-192.

35
00:03:12,463 --> 00:03:18,581
ML-KEM-1024, Category 5, AES-256.

36
00:03:18,581 --> 00:03:28,677
ML-KEM-768 is the common default — a strong balance of security and size, and what many TLS hybrid deployments use today.

37
00:03:28,677 --> 00:03:35,540
Next up: ML-DSA: the signature (FIPS 204, formerly Dilithium).

38
00:03:35,540 --> 00:03:46,298
ML-DSA is a digital signature scheme — the quantum-safe replacement for ECDSA/Ed25519/RSA signatures.

39
00:03:46,298 --> 00:03:47,860
The shape is familiar:

40
00:03:47,860 --> 00:03:51,454
sign(private_key, message) → signature.

41
00:03:51,454 --> 00:03:57,608
verify(public_key, message, signature) → valid / invalid.

42
00:03:57,608 --> 00:04:07,319
You use it anywhere you sign today: tokens (this is what makes QAuth quantum-safe), certificates, code/firmware signing, and software releases.

43
00:04:07,319 --> 00:04:08,846
Its parameter sets:

44
00:04:08,846 --> 00:04:11,141
Parameter set, NIST level.

45
00:04:11,141 --> 00:04:14,531
ML-DSA-44, Category 2.

46
00:04:14,531 --> 00:04:18,677
ML-DSA-65, Category 3.

47
00:04:18,677 --> 00:04:22,620
ML-DSA-87, Category 5.

48
00:04:22,620 --> 00:04:28,137
ML-DSA-65 is the typical default for general-purpose signing.

49
00:04:28,137 --> 00:04:31,899
Let's explore The thing that surprises everyone: the sizes.

50
00:04:31,899 --> 00:04:34,915
Lattice cryptography is fast, but it is big.

51
00:04:34,915 --> 00:04:38,401
This is the practical cost that shapes real deployments.

52
00:04:38,401 --> 00:04:39,951
Approximate sizes:

53
00:04:39,951 --> 00:04:43,846
Scheme, Public key, "Payload", vs classical.

54
00:04:43,846 --> 00:04:49,939
Ed25519 (classical), 32 B, 64 B signature, baseline.

55
00:04:49,939 --> 00:04:57,355
X25519 (classical KEM-ish), 32 B, 32 B, baseline.

56
00:04:57,355 --> 00:05:07,992
ML-KEM-768, ~1,184 B, ~1,088 B ciphertext, ~30–40× larger.

57
00:05:07,992 --> 00:05:17,740
ML-DSA-65, ~1,952 B, ~3,300 B signature, ~50× larger signature.

58
00:05:17,740 --> 00:05:27,331
Read that again: an ML-DSA-65 signature is several kilobytes versus 64 bytes for Ed25519.

59
00:05:27,331 --> 00:05:36,141
The algorithms are computationally fast — often competitive with RSA — but the bytes on the wire are the real engineering consideration.

60
00:05:36,141 --> 00:05:37,295
It inflates:

61
00:05:37,322 --> 00:05:42,067
Tokens — a signed token jumps from a few hundred bytes to several KB..

62
00:05:42,067 --> 00:05:46,442
TLS handshakes — bigger key-exchange and certificate messages..

63
00:05:46,442 --> 00:05:50,288
Certificates — larger public keys and signatures..

64
00:05:50,288 --> 00:05:58,485
For high-QPS APIs or bandwidth-constrained clients (IoT, mobile in low-connectivity regions), measure this.

65
00:05:58,485 --> 00:06:04,195
It rarely blocks adoption, but it absolutely changes your latency and bandwidth budgets.

66
00:06:04,195 --> 00:06:07,608
Now let's look at When to use which — a decision cheat sheet.

67
00:06:07,608 --> 00:06:11,454
Establishing a secure channel / session key?

68
00:06:11,454 --> 00:06:12,632
ML-KEM.

69
00:06:12,632 --> 00:06:16,779
(TLS, VPNs, encrypting data for a recipient.).

70
00:06:16,779 --> 00:06:19,074
Proving who created or approved something?

71
00:06:19,074 --> 00:06:20,324
ML-DSA.

72
00:06:20,324 --> 00:06:24,122
(Tokens, certificates, code signing, document signing.).

73
00:06:24,122 --> 00:06:25,757
Building auth like QAuth?

74
00:06:25,757 --> 00:06:32,139
both: ML-KEM to protect the channel/payload, ML-DSA to sign the token..

75
00:06:32,139 --> 00:06:37,103
Need maximum conservatism for a root of trust / firmware?

76
00:06:37,103 --> 00:06:47,560
consider SLH-DSA (FIPS 205), a hash-based signature with very large signatures but a security argument resting only on hash functions..

77
00:06:47,560 --> 00:06:50,060
Now, let's talk about A note on hybrids.

78
00:06:50,060 --> 00:06:54,171
In practice you rarely deploy these alone in 2026.

79
00:06:54,171 --> 00:07:11,430
The recommended rollout pairs each with a classical algorithm — X25519 + ML-KEM for key exchange, Ed25519 + ML-DSA for signatures — so you're protected if either the classical or the post-quantum scheme is later broken.

80
00:07:11,430 --> 00:07:18,582
The reasoning is in why hybrid Ed25519 + ML-DSA is the safe path.

81
00:07:18,582 --> 00:07:20,180
Moving on to The takeaway.

82
00:07:20,180 --> 00:07:27,969
Keep the two jobs straight and the rest follows: ML-KEM = key exchange, ML-DSA = signatures.

83
00:07:27,969 --> 00:07:41,911
Default to ML-KEM-768 and ML-DSA-65 unless you have a specific reason to go higher or lower, budget for kilobyte-scale keys and signatures, and deploy them in hybrid mode.

84
00:07:41,911 --> 00:07:46,767
Get those choices right and you have the cryptographic core of a quantum-safe system.

85
00:07:46,767 --> 00:07:53,906
